@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="question">@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}}</a> at the end of a sentence can indicate a simple question.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{korehadareno@KJ{{umbrella}}desu@EM{{ka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Whose umbrella is this?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} at the end of a sentence can indicate a question of the form "how about".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}wo@KJ{{see}}ni@KJ{{going}}kimasenn@EM{{ka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How about going to see a film?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} at the end of a sentence can indicate a rhetorical question.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sonnna@KJ{{bad}}i@KJ{{person}}gairumonodesu@EM{{ka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Are there people around as awful as that?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} at the end of a sentence can indicate anger or censure.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mata@KJ{{now^day}}mo,@KJ{{slow}}rete@KJ{{come}}tandesu@EM{{ka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      So you're late again today?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} at the end of a sentence can indicate that someone is talking to himself.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sorosoro@KJ{{summer}}mo@KJ{{end}}wari@EM{{ka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      So summer's almost over huh?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="alternative">Within</a> a sentence, @HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} can indicate a choice: "whether or not".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{ko-hi-}}@EM{{ka}}@KJ{{crimson^tea}}@EM{{ka}}@KJ{{drink}}mitaidesune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Some tea or coffee would be nice wouldn't it?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Within a sentence, @HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} can indicate uncertainty about a state or reason: "I wonder".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kazewohiitano@EM{{ka}},@KJ{{head}}ga@KJ{{pain}}indesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wonder if I've caught a cold - my head hurts.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Within a sentence, @HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} following an interrogative word indicates such
meanings as "anyone, anything, someone, something".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{dare@EM{{ka}}@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sannno@KJ{{electricity^tale^turn^nickname}}wo
      @KJ{{know}}tteimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Does anyone know Yamada's phone number?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Within a sentence, @HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} following other particles, indicates uncertainty or doubt.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}santo@EM{{ka}}iu@KJ{{person}}kara@KJ{{electricity^tale}}gaarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There was a phone call from someone called Yamada or something.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} also appears in the idiomatic expression
@HI{{@EM{{ka}}}} ... @HI{{nai uchi ni}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{station}}ni@KJ{{don}}ku@EM{{ka}}@KJ{{don}}kanaiuchini@KJ{{electricity^car}}ga@KJ{{come}}ta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I had hardly arrived at the station when the train came.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

